info.title: ServiceTitan API v1
info.description:
# Getting Started This document is structured for both business users and engineers that could work with ServiceTitan. We wanted to provide useful use cases (from a business perspective) along with the information needed to understand our APIs and Webhooks (from an engineering perspective). Please go to the "API Operations" and "Webhook Operations" sections for specific examples of the type of APIs and Webhooks that ServiceTitan offers along with their associated Models and Model Schemas. Please contact us at **alliances@servicetitan.com** with any questions. ## Introduction ServiceTitan documentation is based off of the Representational State Transfer (RESTful) architectural style. We want to easily be able to transfer data back and forth between our application and yours, therefore we have four design principles: 1. Use HTTP methods explicitly. 2. Be stateless. 3. Expose directory structure-like URIs. 4. Transfer JavaScript Object Notation (JSON). ServiceTitan API is accessible via the following URL:
[https://api.servicetitan.com/{version}/{entityType}/{id}](https://api.servicetitan.com/%7Bversion%7D/%7Bcontroller%7D/%7Bid) | Name | Value | | ---------- | ------------- | | version | The "version" ServiceTitan is using v1. | | entityType | The "entityType" denotes the type of entities being accessed. The "entityType" could be jobs, projects or invoices. The "entityType" is always referenced in plural form. | | id | The "id" is the optional identifier of entity being accessed. | For example, the correct URL to GET Job (Id:12345) is the following: [https://api.servicetitan.com/v1/jobs/12345](https://api.servicetitan.com/v1/jobs/12345) ## HTTP Methods The API is fully RESTful and the following methods are supported by all controllers: 1. GET “retrieves info”. GET allow to access list of entities or certain entity in depends of whether {id} url part specified or not. 2. POST “inserts info”. POST returns result the same way as GET for single entity. The user can see an error happen or GET JSON of newly created entity as results data field. 3. PUT “updates info”. For example, PUT allows to identify booking by its ServiceTitan identity. Additionally, PUT can allow a booking instance to be updated by its ID in an external system. **GET Method ** ServiceTitan API uses this method for retrieving entities. Usage: GET https://api.servicetitan.com/v1/jobs * This method allows the user to access a list of entities or a specific entity. A specific entity can be retrieved based on {id}. * For example, the https://api.servicetitan.com/v1/jobs URL should be used to access a list of jobs (probably filtered) and, the URL https://api.servicetitan.com/v1/jobs/12345 is used to access Job(Id:12345). * The result of an API call is JSON in most cases. When single entity accessed server reports 200 -OK status code. Response body contains JSON with single field. **POST Method ** ServiceTitan API uses this method for creating new entities. Usage: POST https://api.servicetitan.com/v1/jobs * In case of POST url must NOT contain {id} part. Request body must be JSON where entity field values are specified. Certain format depends of entity type. * POST returns result the same way as GET for single entity. Inspecting result you can see whether an error happen or get JSON of newly created entity as result’s data field. **PUT Method ** ServiceTitan API uses this method for updating entities. Usage: PUT https://api.servicetitan.com/v1/jobs/12345 * The PUT URL must contain {id} part. Request body must be JSON where entity field values are specified. Certain format depends of entity type. * POST returns result the same way as GET for single entity. Inspecting result you can see whether an error happen or get JSON of an updated entity as result’s data field. * PUT request can be emulated by POST request. Just add X-HTTP-Method-Override:PUT header to your POST request. ## Authentication ServiceTitan API supports authentication by API key. Each request must contain this key to be processed correctly. API key could be specified two ways: 1. Via X-HTTP-ServiceTitan-Api-Key Http header. 2. Via serviceTitanApiKey query string parameter. In both cases API key is the same value ServiceTitan administrator can generate for you. # Use Cases We have documented the most typical use cases where a third party can integrate with ServiceTitan along the home services operational management process. There are many more opportunities where a partner can work with ServiceTitan’s APIs and Webhooks. Please contact us at **alliances@servicetitan.com** to discuss potential opportunities. ## Booking Job **Background: **A major process in ServiceTitan is allowing the Customer Service Representative (CSR) to “Book a Job” when a customer calls the office. ServiceTitan pulls in relevant caller information (phone number, name, address, etc.) and then the CSR can book the job by viewing the available schedule of technicians. A third party can provide booking services so the end-user looking for a job can find it via a third party and book the job through the third party portals. The availability of technicians is provided by ServiceTitan to the Booking Websites and Portals. **Booking Website Widget Use Case: **ServiceTitan can provide HTML Snippets so a third party website can copy and paste HTML and plug it into the website to create a “Booking Widget”. ServiceTitan customer’s can utilize this widget to customers can book jobs directly through their websites without having to call their CSRs. 1. Third party (website) can request ServiceTitan for “Booking Widget” code 2. ServiceTitan provides third party with HTML snippets 3. Third party installs HTML snippets on website that could be called “Book an Appointment” 4. When customers to go to the third party site (“Joe’s Pluming”), a booking widget is available for the customer to see a schedule of date/time of availability and schedule an appointment. 5. The customer goes through a checkout process by entering the job information (e.g., job type description, time, date, etc.) 6. The customer checks the “cancellation policy” and continues booking. 7. The customer enters their contact information (name, email, phone, address, etc.) 8. Customer clicks “Book it” and receives an email confirmation on the booked appointment. 9. The third party is notified in ServiceTitan on the new appointment and the CSR is able to adjust information as needed and notify the customer of any changes. **Booking Through Portals Use Case: **Booking APIs allows someone to read, create, and update booking instances (i.e., GET, POST, UPDATE). Third party booking portals can utilize ServiceTitan’s APIs to understand the HVAC, Electrical, and Plumbing companies availability for jobs and the specific date/times of availability. Third party (booking portal) can request ServiceTitan APIs for available companies with availability. ServiceTitan exposes an API that passes along customers' ID code and parameters (e.g., next available technician from company X). ServiceTitan can provide a customized iFrame for the booking portal with pre-built interface that can be customized for the booking portal. 1. A person who wants to find someone to install a bath faucet goes to the Booking Portal and searches for Plumbing companies or types in ‘bath faucet installation’ depending on the Booking Portal capabilities 2. A “Book an Appointment” widget is exposed that allows the customer to find an appointment for a job ( ServiceTitan provides the data needed for the Booking Portal) 3. The user on the Booking Portal clicks on a company name and available options pop up for the customer (e.g., Drain Cleaning, Faucets/Toilets, etc.) 4. The user clicks on “Faucets/Toilets” category and specific job sub-categories pop up (e.g., Unclog Toilet, Leaky Faucet, Install New Toilet, Install Shower Head, Install Bath Faucet, Install Kitchen Faucet, etc.) 5. The user clicks on “Install Bath Faucet” and a calendar pops up showing available dates and times 6. The user picks the dates an time, checks the cancellation policy and clicks “Continue Booking” 7. The customer enters their contact information (name, email, phone, address, etc.) 8. Customer clicks “Book it” and receives an email confirmation on the booked appointment through the Booking Portal 9. The appointment and job data gets populated in ServiceTitan and the plumbing company is notified on the new appointment with job details 10. The ServiceTitan plumbing company can update the job and notify the customer and the Booking Portal receives updates from ServiceTitan on these or any other job related updates ## Dispatching Job **Background: **The event when a technician is dispatched to a job can create opportunities to notify the customer or help the technician on his/her way to the job. Dispatching APIs occur when the technician starts the process of traveling to the job site. An example is that a ServiceTitan partner can use this API to communicate to the customer that a technician is on the way. **Dispatch Triggers an Email to Customer Use Case: **A third party can pull job and technician data when the technician is dispatched. Today, customers want to know as much information as possible as the person who is entering their residence. An email could be sent to the customer as soon as the technician is dispatched so the customer knows who is coming, arrival time, information about the job, etc. 1. Job that is scheduled in ServiceTitan is getting close to the time of appointment 2. Technician is dispatched to the job to arrive at the time of appointment 3. ServiceTitan notifies a third party that the technician has been dispatched 4. The notification triggers the third party to send a “reminder email” to the customer about the appointment 5. The email can include the technician bio, background check, estimated time of arrival, etc. 6. The customer receives the reminder from the third party and reviews the job/technician information and awaits for his/her arrival **Dispatch Triggers Technician to Be Tracked Real-Time Use Case: **A GPS service company can load ServiceTitan data on their devices. This way the job data can be synched to the installed GPS devices and help navigate a technician to a job through the GPS devices as opposed to utilizing a mobile device or tablet (i.e., iPad). 1. Job that is scheduled in ServiceTitan is getting close to the time of appointment 2. Technician is dispatched to the job to arrive at the time of appointment 3. GPS device is triggered and routes the directions for the technician 4. The technician utilizes the GPS device to drive to the job 5. Technician arrives at the job and the GPS device records history of the route and job ## Arriving at Job **Background:** One of the most important steps in the home services operation management process is when the technician arrives at the job, views opportunities, and sells/completes the job. In today's home services business, the technician is responsible to understand the potential problem(s) at the home and facilitate a ‘selling process’ to gather estimate job opportunities and agree with the customer on the job. The technician “putting on his/her selling hat on” is not typically part of their core competencies, therefore there are many opportunities to help the technician in the selling process. **Third Party Selling Tool Use Case: **ServiceTitan can integrate with “Third Party Selling Tools” to help facilitate this process. A third party can develop any type of App for ServiceTitan, and since this is such a integral process for the technician, there is value in potential opportunities to improve the technician workflow. 1. The technician arrives at the job, enters the home, and meets the customer. 2. The technician opens up the ServiceTitan mobile app to view the job details and customer information. 3. In the ServiceTitan App, a button is available for a “Third Party Selling Tool” 4. The technician clicks on the “Third Party Selling Tool” button and it launches the mobile app and it pulls in all relevant data from ServiceTitan 5. The technician utilizes the “Third Party Selling Tool” app to document opportunities, create estimates, and finalize invoices 6. Once the technician is done, the information is saved and the technician is taken back to the ServiceTitan App where all the information is updated 7. The data stored in both apps can be used for many opportunities (e.g., marketing, replenishment, payment processing, etc.) ## Completing Job **Background: **There are multiple customer retention opportunities after a job is completed by a technician and a third party integrating with ServiceTitan can enhance this process. When a technician completes a job, potential ServiceTitan partners could receive information that can help with understanding how the job went from the customers perspective or help with marketing. For example, once the job is completed, a survey could be sent to the customer to understand the job satisfaction. Another example is that if the customer spent over $1,000 on the job, it could trigger a gift card or a special thank you from the technician’s company. **Job Completion Triggers Survey to Customer Use Case: **Customer satisfaction is an integral part for a HVAC, Electrical, or Plumbing companies to receive repeat business in the future. The home services business want to make sure that their customers are happy with the jobs and will continue to do business with them. An easy way to understand if a customer was satisfied is sending them a survey after job completion. 1. The technician completes the job and the customer signs the invoice in the ServiceTitan App 2. The job completion triggers a third party to send an email survey to the customer (at a specific time after the job) 3. The email could contain any type of information about the job, technician, and customer that ServiceTitan stores 4. The customer receives the email from the third party and completes the survey 5. The survey results are sent back to home services company so they can understand customer satisfaction 6. The survey results could also trigger the customer to conduct reviews on any number of reputation portals (e.g., Yelp, Facebook, Google, etc.) 7. That data received from the home services company can be used for future opportunities with the customer, marketing automation opportunities, and many other lead opportunities # API Overview **What is an API? **An Application Programming Interface (API) is a set of routines, protocols, and tools for building software applications. An API allows one software application to talk with another software application securely over the Internet. A software company releases its API to the public so that other software developers can design products that are powered by its service. A good API makes it easier to develop a program by providing all the building blocks. A programmer then puts the blocks together. These are examples of the typical APIs utilized for ServiceTitan. * **Booking Jobs** - One of the integral parts of ServiceTitan is allowing the Customer Service Representative (CSR) to "Book a Job" when a customer calls the office. ServiceTitan pulls in relevant caller information (phone number, name, address, etc.) and then the CSR can book the job by viewing the available schedule of technicians. ServiceTitan can provide HTML Snippets so you can copy and paste HTML and plug it into your website to create a "Booking Widget". Booking APIs allows someone to read, create, and update booking instances (i.e., GET, POST, UPDATE). * **Dispatching Jobs** - A dispatch occurs when the technician starts the process of traveling to the job site. The "dispatch" in ServiceTitan can trigger events that can potentially help the person who is eventually going to meet the technician. An example is that a ServiceTitan partner can use this API to communicate to the customer that a technician is on the way. * **Arriving at Jobs** - When a technician arrives at the job, their responsibility is to understand the potential problem and facilitate a 'selling process' to gather estimate job opportunities and agree with the customer on the job. ServiceTitan can integrate with "Third Party Selling Tools" to help facilitate this process. * **Completing Job** - When a technician completes a job, potential ServiceTitan partners could receive information that can help with understanding how the job went from the customers perspective or help with marketing. For example, once the job is completed, a survey could be sent to the customer to understand the job satisfaction. Another example is that if the customer spent over $1,000, this could trigger a gift card or a special thank you from the technician's company. The API Operations section describes the operations performed by ServiceTitan and the ability to GET, POST, and PUT information via APIs. #API Operations

get.description:
Bookings API allows to read, create, and update booking instances. It is possible to create bookings from different sources and distinguish between those sources. This is organized as following: each API key is internally tagged with some value in ServiceTitan. Bookings API in turn provides access only to booking instances were created with help of an API key tagged the same as API key of current request.

GET = https://api.servicetitan.com/v1/bookings?{query-string}

post.description:
A new booking can be created with the following request:
POST = https://api.servicetitan.com/v1/bookings
